# Edit - Script Editor and Creator

**Version:** 2.5  
**Author:** Julio Cesar Garcia  
**Date:** March 5, 2025  
**Part of:** [JC Scripts Collection](https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts)

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Overview](#overview)
2. [Features](#features)
3. [Installation](#installation)
4. [Usage](#usage)
5. [Command Reference](#command-reference)
6. [Creating New Scripts](#creating-new-scripts)
7. [Editing Existing Scripts](#editing-existing-scripts)
8. [Script Template](#script-template)
9. [Examples](#examples)
10. [Configuration](#configuration)
11. [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)
12. [Best Practices](#best-practices)
13. [Quick Reference](#quick-reference)

---

## Overview

The `edit` command is a smart script editor that simplifies creating and modifying scripts in the JC Scripts Collection. It:

- **Creates new scripts** with a professional template
- **Opens existing scripts** in your preferred editor
- **Validates script names** to prevent conflicts
- **Sets proper permissions** automatically
- **Prevents overwriting** system commands

This tool ensures consistency across all scripts in the collection and makes script development fast and error-free.

**Part of the JC Scripts Collection:** This utility is designed to work seamlessly with the [JC Scripts Collection](https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts), respecting configuration settings and maintaining collection standards.

---

## Features

### Core Capabilities

✅ **Smart Script Creation**
- Generates scripts with professional header template
- Auto-fills metadata (author, date, version)
- Sets executable permissions automatically
- Validates names to prevent conflicts

✅ **Conflict Prevention**
- Checks against shell built-ins (cd, ls, etc.)
- Checks against system commands (/bin, /usr/bin)
- Validates character usage in names
- Prevents empty or invalid names

✅ **Template System**
- Standardized header format
- Pre-configured help function
- Version display function
- Main function structure
- Usage documentation placeholder

✅ **Editor Integration**
- Respects `EDITOR` environment variable
- Reads from `~/.jcscripts` configuration
- Fallback to `vi` if not configured
- Opens script immediately after creation

✅ **Existing Script Editing**
- Bypasses validation for existing scripts
- Allows editing of any name (including system commands)
- Quick access to script modification
- No unnecessary checks

---

## Installation

### As Part of JC Scripts Collection (Recommended)

The `edit` command is automatically installed with the JC Scripts Collection:

```bash
# Clone repository
git clone https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts.git ~/.scripts

# Install prerequisites
cd ~/.scripts && ./installextras

# Setup scripts (includes 'edit')
./installscripts

# Reload shell
source ~/.bashrc
```

### Standalone Installation

```bash
# Create directory
mkdir -p ~/.scripts

# Download edit script
curl -sSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ingasti/jcscripts/main/edit -o ~/.scripts/edit

# Make executable
chmod +x ~/.scripts/edit

# Add to PATH
echo 'export PATH="$HOME/.scripts:$PATH"' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc

# Create configuration file
cat > ~/.scripts/.jcscripts << 'EOF'
SCRIPTS_DIR="~/.scripts"
EDITOR="vi"
EOF
```

---

## Usage

### Basic Syntax

```bash
edit [script_name]
edit [options]
```

### Quick Start

```bash
# Create a new script
edit myscript

# Edit an existing script
edit awslogin

# Show help
edit --help

# Show version
edit --version
```

---

## Command Reference

| Option | Short | Description |
|--------|-------|-------------|
| `--help` | `-h` | Display help message and usage information |
| `--version` | `-v` | Show edit script version |
| `<script_name>` | - | Name of script to create or edit |

### Usage Patterns

**Create New Script:**
```bash
edit newscript
```
- Validates name
- Checks for conflicts
- Creates template
- Opens in editor

**Edit Existing Script:**
```bash
edit existingscript
```
- Skips validation
- Opens directly in editor
- No name restrictions

**Show Help:**
```bash
edit -h
edit --help
```

**Show Version:**
```bash
edit -v
edit --version
```

---

## Creating New Scripts

### Creation Workflow

```
Input Name → Validate → Check Conflicts → Create Template → Set Permissions → Open Editor
```

### Name Validation

**Valid Characters:**
- Letters (a-z, A-Z)
- Numbers (0-9)
- Dots (.)
- Underscores (_)
- Hyphens (-)

**Invalid Characters:**
- Spaces
- Special characters (@, #, $, %, etc.)
- Path separators (/)

**Example Valid Names:**
```bash
edit myscript          # ✓ Simple name
edit my_script         # ✓ With underscore
edit my-script         # ✓ With hyphen
edit my.script         # ✓ With dot
edit myscript2         # ✓ With number
```

**Example Invalid Names:**
```bash
edit my script         # ✗ Contains space
edit my@script         # ✗ Special character
edit my/script         # ✗ Path separator
edit "my script"       # ✗ Quoted space
```

### Conflict Detection

**Checks Against:**

1. **Shell Built-ins:**
   - `cd`, `ls`, `pwd`, `echo`, etc.
   - Any command recognized by `type`

2. **System Commands:**
   - Anything in `$PATH`
   - `/bin`, `/usr/bin`, `/usr/local/bin`

3. **Existing Scripts:**
   - If script exists, opens for editing
   - No conflict check performed

**Example Conflicts:**
```bash
edit cd                # ✗ Shell built-in
edit ls                # ✗ System command
edit mkdir             # ✗ System command
edit aws               # ✗ If AWS CLI installed
```

**Bypass for Existing:**
```bash
# If ~/.scripts/cd already exists:
edit cd                # ✓ Opens existing file (conflict check skipped)
```

### Template Generation

When creating a new script, `edit` generates:

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Script Name:    myscript
# Description:    Add your description here.
# Usage:          Add your usage here.
# Author:         jcgarcia
# Date:           22/11/2025
# Version:        1.0
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Display usage information
show_help() {
  echo "Usage: ./myscript [options]"
  echo "Options:"
  echo "  -h | --help    Show this help message"
  echo "  -v | --version Show script version"
}

# Display script version
show_version() {
  echo "myscript version 1.0"
}

# Main script logic
main() {
  echo "Welcome to $0!"
  echo "Add your code logic here."
}

# Execute the main function
main "$@"
```

**Auto-filled Fields:**
- Script Name: From command argument
- Author: From `$LOGNAME` environment variable
- Date: Current date in DD/MM/YYYY format
- Version: Defaults to 1.0

**Placeholders:**
- Description: "Add your description here."
- Usage: "Add your usage here."

### Permissions

Scripts are created with executable permissions:

```bash
chmod +x "$script_path"
```

Equivalent to:
```bash
-rwxr-xr-x
```

---

## Editing Existing Scripts

### Direct Edit Mode

When script exists in `~/.scripts/`:

```
Check Existence → Open in Editor
```

**No validation performed:**
- ✅ Name conflicts allowed
- ✅ Any name accepted
- ✅ Immediate editor launch

### Example Session

```bash
$ edit awslogin
Opening existing script with vi: /home/user/.scripts/awslogin

# Editor opens immediately
# Make changes
# Save and exit
```

### Editing Scripts with Conflicting Names

```bash
# These work fine if script already exists
edit cd                # Edit existing 'cd' script
edit ls                # Edit existing 'ls' script
edit test              # Edit existing 'test' script
```

---

## Script Template

### Standard Header Format

All scripts created by `edit` follow this format:

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Script Name:    <name>
# Description:    <description>
# Usage:          <usage>
# Author:         <author>
# Date:           <DD/MM/YYYY>
# Version:        <version>
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
```

### Standard Functions

**Help Function:**
```bash
show_help() {
  echo "Usage: ./<script> [options]"
  echo "Options:"
  echo "  -h | --help    Show this help message"
  echo "  -v | --version Show script version"
}
```

**Version Function:**
```bash
show_version() {
  echo "<script> version <version>"
}
```

**Main Function:**
```bash
main() {
  echo "Welcome to $0!"
  echo "Add your code logic here."
}
```

### Entry Point

```bash
main "$@"
```

Passes all command-line arguments to main function.

---

## Examples

### Example 1: Create Simple Utility Script

```bash
# Create new script
edit backup-db

# Editor opens with template
# Modify description
# Add functionality
# Save and exit

# Script is ready to use
chmod +x ~/.scripts/backup-db    # Already done automatically
backup-db
```

### Example 2: Create AWS Helper Script

```bash
# Create AWS-related script
edit aws-list-instances

# Template generated
# Add AWS CLI commands
# Save

# Use immediately
aws-list-instances
```

### Example 3: Edit Existing Script

```bash
# Quick edit
edit awslogin

# Make changes
# Save
# Test
awslogin
```

### Example 4: Create Script with Configuration

```bash
# First, set preferred editor
echo 'EDITOR="nano"' >> ~/.jcscripts

# Create script (opens in nano)
edit configure-db

# Template opens in nano
# Edit and save
```

### Example 5: Handle Name Conflict Error

```bash
$ edit ls
Error: Script name 'ls' conflicts with an existing shell built-in or system command. Please choose another name.

# Choose different name
$ edit list-files
Creating a new script: list-files...
Opening script with vi: /home/user/.scripts/list-files
```

### Example 6: Batch Script Creation

```bash
# Create multiple related scripts
for script in backup-start backup-stop backup-status; do
  edit $script
done

# Each opens in editor sequentially
# Edit, save, continue to next
```

---

## Configuration

### Configuration File

**Location:** `~/.scripts/.jcscripts`

**Format:**
```bash
# Configuration for JC Scripts Collection
SCRIPTS_DIR="~/.scripts"
EDITOR="vi"
```

### Variables

**SCRIPTS_DIR:**
- Where scripts are stored
- Default: `~/.scripts`
- Can use `~` (expanded to `$HOME`)
- Must be absolute path or `~` relative

**EDITOR:**
- Command to open scripts
- Default: `vi`
- Examples: `vim`, `nano`, `emacs`, `code`, `subl`

### Setting Your Editor

**Method 1: Edit Configuration File**
```bash
nano ~/.scripts/.jcscripts

# Change line:
EDITOR="nano"
```

**Method 2: Command Line**
```bash
echo 'EDITOR="nano"' >> ~/.scripts/.jcscripts
```

**Method 3: Environment Variable**
```bash
export EDITOR="nano"
# Add to ~/.bashrc for persistence
```

### Supported Editors

**Terminal Editors:**
- `vi` / `vim` - Default, always available
- `nano` - User-friendly
- `emacs` - Powerful, extensible
- `joe` - Lightweight

**GUI Editors (require X11 or local desktop):**
- `code` - Visual Studio Code
- `subl` - Sublime Text
- `gedit` - GNOME Text Editor
- `atom` - Atom Editor

---

## Troubleshooting

### Problem: "Invalid script name" Error

**Symptoms:**
```
Error: Invalid script name: my@script. Please use only letters, numbers, dots, underscores, or hyphens.
```

**Cause:** Script name contains invalid characters

**Solution:**
```bash
# Remove special characters
edit my-script        # Use hyphen instead of @
edit my_script        # Use underscore
edit myscript         # Remove separator
```

### Problem: "Conflicts with existing command" Error

**Symptoms:**
```
Error: Script name 'test' conflicts with an existing shell built-in or system command.
```

**Cause:** Name matches shell built-in or system command

**Solutions:**

**Option 1: Choose different name**
```bash
edit mytest
edit test-util
edit run-test
```

**Option 2: Use prefix**
```bash
edit jc-test
edit custom-test
```

**Option 3: Edit existing (if it exists)**
```bash
# If ~/.scripts/test already exists
edit test             # Opens existing, bypasses check
```

### Problem: Editor not found

**Symptoms:**
```
bash: nano: command not found
```

**Cause:** Configured editor not installed

**Solutions:**

**Install the editor:**
```bash
# Ubuntu/Debian
sudo apt install nano

# Fedora
sudo dnf install nano

# Arch
sudo pacman -S nano

# Alpine
sudo apk add nano
```

**Or change to available editor:**
```bash
# Use vi (always available)
echo 'EDITOR="vi"' > ~/.scripts/.jcscripts
```

### Problem: Script created but not executable

**Symptoms:**
```bash
./myscript
bash: ./myscript: Permission denied
```

**Cause:** Permissions not set (shouldn't happen with `edit`)

**Solution:**
```bash
# Make executable
chmod +x ~/.scripts/myscript

# Verify
ls -l ~/.scripts/myscript
# Should show: -rwxr-xr-x
```

### Problem: Script not in PATH

**Symptoms:**
```bash
myscript
bash: myscript: command not found
```

**Cause:** `~/.scripts` not in PATH

**Solution:**
```bash
# Add to PATH
echo 'export PATH="$HOME/.scripts:$PATH"' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc

# Verify
echo $PATH | grep ".scripts"
```

### Problem: Configuration file not found

**Symptoms:**
```
Warning: Configuration file '/home/user/.scripts/.jcscripts' not found. Using default settings.
```

**Cause:** Configuration file missing

**Solutions:**

**Recreate configuration:**
```bash
cat > ~/.scripts/.jcscripts << 'EOF'
SCRIPTS_DIR="~/.scripts"
EDITOR="vi"
EOF
```

**Or run installscripts:**
```bash
cd ~/.scripts && ./installscripts
```

### Problem: Template has wrong author/date

**Cause:** Environment variables incorrect

**Solution:**

**Check `$LOGNAME`:**
```bash
echo $LOGNAME
# Should show your username
```

**If wrong, edit script after creation:**
```bash
edit myscript
# Manually correct Author field
```

---

## Best Practices

### Naming Conventions

**Good Names:**
```bash
edit backup-database           # Descriptive with hyphen
edit aws-list-ec2             # Prefixed, descriptive
edit restore_db               # Descriptive with underscore
edit dbmigrate                # Single word, clear
```

**Avoid:**
```bash
edit script                   # Too generic
edit a                        # Too short
edit my-super-long-script-name-for-backups  # Too long
```

### Template Customization

**Always Update:**
1. **Description:** Replace "Add your description here"
2. **Usage:** Add actual usage syntax
3. **Main Function:** Remove welcome message, add real code

**Example Before:**
```bash
# Description:    Add your description here.
# Usage:          Add your usage here.
```

**Example After:**
```bash
# Description:    Backup PostgreSQL database to S3
# Usage:          backup-database <database> <bucket>
```

### Version Management

**Increment version when:**
- Adding new features
- Fixing bugs
- Changing behavior

**Version format:**
```bash
# Version:        1.0     # Initial release
# Version:        1.1     # Minor update
# Version:        2.0     # Major change
```

### Editor Workflow

**For Quick Edits:**
```bash
# Use vi/vim for speed
EDITOR="vi" edit script
```

**For Complex Scripts:**
```bash
# Use full-featured editor
EDITOR="code" edit script
```

**For Remote Servers:**
```bash
# Use terminal-only editors
EDITOR="nano" edit script
```

---

## Quick Reference

### Common Commands

```bash
# Create new script
edit myscript

# Edit existing script
edit existing-script

# Show help
edit -h

# Show version
edit -v
```

### Name Validation Rules

| Rule | Valid | Invalid |
|------|-------|---------|
| Letters | `abc`, `ABC` | - |
| Numbers | `123`, `test2` | - |
| Underscore | `my_script` | - |
| Hyphen | `my-script` | - |
| Dot | `my.script` | - |
| Spaces | - | `my script` |
| Special chars | - | `my@script` |
| Path separators | - | `path/script` |

### Configuration Quick Setup

```bash
# Set your editor
echo 'EDITOR="nano"' >> ~/.scripts/.jcscripts

# Verify configuration
cat ~/.scripts/.jcscripts

# Test
edit test-script
```

### Template Modification Checklist

- [ ] Update Description
- [ ] Update Usage
- [ ] Remove welcome message
- [ ] Add actual functionality
- [ ] Test help function
- [ ] Test version function
- [ ] Update version number
- [ ] Add any needed options

---

