# installscripts - JC Scripts Collection Setup

**Version:** 4.0  
**Author:** Julio Cesar Garcia  
**Last Updated:** 2025-11-20  
**Part of:** [JC Scripts Collection](../README.md)

---

## Table of Contents

- [Overview](#overview)
- [Features](#features)
- [Prerequisites](#prerequisites)
- [Installation](#installation)
- [Usage](#usage)
- [Command Reference](#command-reference)
- [Advanced Features](#advanced-features)
- [Workflow Examples](#workflow-examples)
- [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)
- [Technical Details](#technical-details)
- [Quick Reference](#quick-reference)

---

## Overview

`installscripts` is the primary installation script for the JC Scripts Collection. It automates the complete setup process including extracting scripts, configuring the environment, fixing compatibility issues, and updating your PATH.

### What It Does

- Clones the jcscripts repository from GitHub
- Extracts scripts from the library archive
- Makes scripts executable
- Fixes line ending issues (CRLF to LF)
- Creates default configuration file
- Updates PATH in shell profile
- Installs optional dependencies
- Validates installation

### Why Use It

- One-command installation process
- Automatic dependency detection
- Cross-platform compatibility (works on multiple Linux distributions)
- Safe and reversible setup
- Handles shell configuration automatically

---

## Features

- **Repository Management** - Clones or updates from GitHub
- **Script Extraction** - Unpacks scripts from library archive
- **Auto-Configuration** - Creates default .jcscripts config
- **PATH Management** - Updates shell profile automatically
- **Line Ending Fixes** - Converts Windows CRLF to Unix LF
- **Dependency Checking** - Validates required tools
- **Multi-Shell Support** - Works with bash, ash, ksh, csh/tcsh
- **Session Refresh** - Applies changes immediately
- **Help System** - Built-in documentation

---

## Prerequisites

### Required Tools (Auto-Installed)

The script checks for and offers to install:
- `git` - Version control
- `ar` (binutils) - Archive extraction
- `column` (util-linux) - Text formatting  
- `tput` (ncurses) - Terminal control
- `jq` - JSON processing
- `curl` - File downloads
- `unzip` - Archive extraction

### Quick Prerequisites Installation

```bash
# Automatic installation (recommended)
./installextras

# Manual installation (Ubuntu/Debian)
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y git binutils util-linux ncurses-bin jq curl unzip

# Manual installation (Fedora/RHEL)
sudo dnf install -y git binutils util-linux ncurses jq curl unzip

# Manual installation (Arch Linux)
sudo pacman -S --noconfirm git binutils util-linux ncurses jq curl unzip

# Manual installation (Alpine)
sudo apk add git binutils util-linux ncurses jq curl unzip bash file findutils
```

---

## Installation

### Standard Installation

```bash
# 1. Download installscripts
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jcgarcia/jcscripts/main/installscripts
chmod +x installscripts

# 2. Install prerequisites (recommended)
./installextras  # Auto-installs all dependencies

# 3. Run installation
./installscripts

# 4. Reload shell configuration
source ~/.bashrc  # or source ~/.profile for ash/ksh
```

### One-Liner Installation

```bash
# Using auto-installer (downloads and runs installscripts)
curl -sSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jcgarcia/jcscripts/main/auto-installer | bash
```

### Manual Installation Steps

```bash
# Clone repository manually
git clone https://github.com/jcgarcia/jcscripts.git ~/.scripts
cd ~/.scripts

# Run installation
./installscripts
```

---

## Configuration

### Default Configuration File

The script creates `~/.scripts/.jcscripts` and `~/.jcscripts`:

```bash
# Configuration for scripts
EDITOR="vi"
SCRIPTS_DIR="~/.scripts"
GITHUB_REPO="git@github.com:jcgarcia/jcscripts.git"
SSH_KEY="~/.ssh/jc.pem"
```

### Customizing Configuration

Edit `~/.jcscripts` or `~/.scripts/.jcscripts`:

```bash
vi ~/.jcscripts

# Change editor
EDITOR="nano"  # or "code", "vim", etc.

# Change scripts directory
SCRIPTS_DIR="~/my-scripts"

# Add custom variables
MY_AWS_REGION="us-east-1"
```

---

## Usage

### Basic Syntax

```bash
installscripts [OPTIONS]
```

### Command Options

```bash
installscripts              # Run installation
installscripts -h           # Show help
installscripts --help       # Show help
installscripts -v           # Show version
installscripts --version    # Show version
```

---

## Command Reference

### Options

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `-h, --help` | Display help message and exit |
| `-v, --version` | Display script version |

### Exit Codes

| Code | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `0` | Installation successful |
| `1` | Error occurred (missing tools, failed extraction, etc.) |

---

## Advanced Features

### Automatic Dependency Installation

If required tools are missing, the script will attempt to install them:

```bash
# Detected missing tools
Installing missing tool: ar (package: binutils)...
Installing missing tool: jq (package: jq)...
```

### AWS CLI Detection

Detects if AWS CLI is installed and offers installation:

```bash
WARNING: AWS CLI is not installed. AWS-related scripts will not work.

You can install AWS CLI by running (after installing the scripts):
  ./awsinstall

Continue without AWS CLI? (y/n):
```

### Shell Detection and Configuration

Automatically detects your shell and updates the appropriate configuration file:

- **bash** → `~/.bashrc`
- **ash** → `~/.profile`
- **ksh** → `~/.kshrc`
- **csh/tcsh** → `~/.cshrc`

### Repository Sync

If `~/.scripts` already exists:

```bash
The directory ~/.scripts already exists. Pulling the latest changes...
Resetting local branch to match remote branch...
```

---

## Workflow Examples

### Example 1: First Time Installation

```bash
$ ./installscripts
Starting installation process...
Cloning the repository into /home/user/.scripts...
Checking for required tools...
ar is already installed.
column is already installed.
tput is already installed.
jq is already installed.
git is already installed.
curl is already installed.
unzip is already installed.
AWS CLI is already installed: aws-cli/2.13.0

Creating or updating default configuration file: ~/.scripts/.jcscripts...
Default configuration file created or updated.
