# New Git Project Script - Planning Document

## Overview
Create a structured script to initialize new Git projects with proper organization, dual repository setup (private org + public user), and AI-assisted workflow support.

## Project Structure

### Root Project Folder (e.g., `MyAppProj/`)
```
MyAppProj/
├── .git/                      # Main git repo (private - Ingasti org)
├── .gitignore
├── README.md                  # Project overview and documentation
├── LICENSE
├── activity/                  # Development activity tracking
│   ├── README.md             # Activity folder guide
│   ├── status/               # **NEW** Session status and context saves
│   │   ├── README.md         # How to use status saves
│   │   ├── session-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM.md  # Session context snapshots
│   │   └── current-context.md # Always current session state
│   ├── vibe/                 # **NEW** AI instructions and prompts
│   │   ├── README.md         # Vibe folder guide
│   │   ├── ai-instructions.md # General AI behavior/context
│   │   ├── prompts/          # Reusable prompt templates
│   │   │   ├── code-review.md
│   │   │   ├── sprint-planning.md
│   │   │   ├── bug-fix.md
│   │   │   └── refactoring.md
│   │   └── project-context.md # Project-specific AI context
│   ├── planning/             # Action plans and roadmaps
│   │   ├── README.md
│   │   └── action-plan-template.md
│   ├── snapshots/            # Git snapshots and archives
│   │   ├── README.md
│   │   ├── session-contexts/ # Historical session contexts
│   │   └── status-reports/   # Historical status reports
│   ├── sprints/              # Sprint documentation
│   │   ├── README.md
│   │   └── sprint-template.md
│   └── templates/            # Reusable templates
│       ├── backup-template.md
│       ├── sprint-template.md
│       ├── status-template.md     # **NEW**
│       └── planning-template.md
├── docs/                     # Project documentation
│   ├── README.md             # Documentation index
│   ├── architecture/         # System architecture docs
│   ├── api/                  # API documentation
│   └── guides/               # User/developer guides
└── MyApp/                    # Public repository (monorepo with pnpm)
    ├── .git/                 # Public git repo (jcgarcia user)
    ├── README.md             # Public-facing README
    ├── package.json          # Root package.json
    ├── pnpm-workspace.yaml   # pnpm workspace configuration
    ├── pnpm-lock.yaml        # pnpm lockfile
    ├── .gitignore
    ├── api/                  # Backend API component
    │   ├── package.json
    │   ├── src/
    │   └── ...
    ├── frontend/             # Frontend web app component
    │   ├── package.json
    │   ├── src/
    │   └── ...
    ├── android/              # Android native app
    │   ├── package.json
    │   └── ...
    └── ios/                  # iOS native app
        ├── package.json
        └── ...
```

## Dual Repository Setup

### Repository Configuration
- **Private Repo**: `git@github.com:Ingasti/MyAppProj.git`
  - Contains: Full project including activity/, docs/, and public code
  - Access: Organization members only
  - Purpose: Development, planning, internal docs

- **Public Repo**: `git@github.com:jcgarcia/MyApp.git`
  - Contains: Only public-facing code and documentation
  - Access: Public internet (HTTPS: `https://github.com/jcgarcia/MyApp.git`)
  - Purpose: Open source distribution, public collaboration

### Implementation Options

#### Option 1: Git Submodule
```bash
# Inside MyAppProj/
git submodule add git@github.com:jcgarcia/MyApp.git MyApp
```
**Pros**: Clean separation, single command to update
**Cons**: Submodule complexity, need to commit in both repos

#### Option 2: Separate Directory + Symlink
```bash
# MyApp is a separate clone, linked from MyAppProj
ln -s ~/projects/MyApp ~/projects/MyAppProj/MyApp
```
**Pros**: Independent git histories, simpler workflow
**Cons**: Need to manage two separate repos manually

#### Option 3: Subtree (Recommended for this use case)
```bash
# Add public repo as subtree
git subtree add --prefix=MyApp git@github.com:jcgarcia/MyApp.git main
```
**Pros**: Single repo workflow, can push to both, cleaner for this pattern
**Cons**: Slightly more complex commands

## Configuration System

### Configuration File: `.gitproject.conf`
Store in project root with git repo information:

```ini
# Git Project Configuration
PROJECT_NAME="MyAppProj"
PROJECT_TYPE="webapp"  # webapp, library, docs, script, monorepo, etc.
USE_MONOREPO="true"    # Always true for code projects
PACKAGE_MANAGER="pnpm" # Always pnpm for monorepos

# Private Repository (Organization)
PRIVATE_ORG="Ingasti"
PRIVATE_REPO="MyAppProj"
PRIVATE_REMOTE="git@github.com:Ingasti/MyAppProj.git"

# Public Repository (User)
PUBLIC_USER="jcgarcia"
PUBLIC_REPO="MyApp"
PUBLIC_REMOTE="git@github.com:jcgarcia/MyApp.git"
PUBLIC_REMOTE_HTTPS="https://github.com/jcgarcia/MyApp.git"

# Public folder location
PUBLIC_DIR="MyApp"

# Author Information
AUTHOR_NAME="Julio Cesar Garcia"
AUTHOR_EMAIL="your-email@example.com"

# Dates
CREATED_DATE="$(date +%Y-%m-%d)"
```

### Global Configuration: `~/.jcscripts`
Add global defaults:
```bash
# Git Configuration
DEFAULT_PRIVATE_ORG="Ingasti"
DEFAULT_PUBLIC_USER="jcgarcia"
DEFAULT_AUTHOR_NAME="Julio Cesar Garcia"
DEFAULT_AUTHOR_EMAIL="your-email@example.com"
```

