# Scripts - JC Scripts Collection Manager

**Version:** 5.2  
**Author:** Julio Cesar Garcia  
**Date:** March 20, 2025  
**Part of:** [JC Scripts Collection](https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts)

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Overview](#overview)
2. [Features](#features)
3. [Installation](#installation)
4. [Usage](#usage)
5. [Command Reference](#command-reference)
6. [Viewing Modes](#viewing-modes)
7. [Update Management](#update-management)
8. [Examples](#examples)
9. [Configuration](#configuration)
10. [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)
11. [Technical Details](#technical-details)
12. [Quick Reference](#quick-reference)

---

## Overview

The `scripts` command is the central management tool for the JC Scripts Collection. It provides a comprehensive interface for:

- **Listing all available scripts** with detailed information
- **Viewing script metadata** (name, description, usage, version, author)
- **Updating the entire collection** from the GitHub repository
- **Multiple display modes** for different use cases

This is typically the first command users run to discover what tools are available in the collection.

**Part of the JC Scripts Collection:** This is a core management utility that works with all other scripts in the [JC Scripts Collection](https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts). It's automatically installed when you set up the collection using `installscripts`.

---

## Features

### Core Capabilities

✅ **Script Discovery**
- Automatically finds all executable scripts in `~/.scripts`
- Excludes hidden files and files with extensions
- Filters only valid shell scripts

✅ **Multiple Display Modes**
- Detailed view with full metadata (default)
- Compact green list view
- Column-based display
- Paginated output with color support

✅ **Metadata Extraction**
- Script name
- Description
- Usage instructions
- Author information
- Creation date
- Version number

✅ **Update Management**
- Check for updates from GitHub repository
- Compare local vs remote versions
- Interactive update confirmation
- Force update option
- Automatic installation of latest version

✅ **Configuration Support**
- Reads from `~/.jcscripts` configuration file
- Respects custom `SCRIPTS_DIR` settings
- Fallback to default values if config not found

---

## Installation

### As Part of JC Scripts Collection (Recommended)

The `scripts` command is automatically installed when you set up the JC Scripts Collection:

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts.git ~/.scripts

# Install prerequisites
cd ~/.scripts && ./installextras

# Setup scripts (includes 'scripts' command)
./installscripts

# Reload shell
source ~/.bashrc
```

See the [main README](https://github.com/Ingasti/jcscripts#getting-started) for complete installation instructions.

### Standalone Installation

If you only want the `scripts` command (not recommended):

```bash
# Ensure directory exists
mkdir -p ~/.scripts

# Download the script
curl -sSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ingasti/jcscripts/main/scripts -o ~/.scripts/scripts

# Download required dependency
curl -sSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ingasti/jcscripts/main/colorfunctions -o ~/.scripts/colorfunctions

# Make executable
chmod +x ~/.scripts/scripts

# Add to PATH
echo 'export PATH="$HOME/.scripts:$PATH"' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc
```

---

## Usage

### Basic Syntax

```bash
scripts [options]
```

### Quick Start

```bash
# List all scripts with full details (default)
scripts

# Show compact list in green
scripts --show

# Check for updates
scripts --update

# Force update even if versions match
scripts --force
```

---

## Command Reference

| Option | Short | Description |
|--------|-------|-------------|
| `--show` | `-s` | Display scripts in compact green list |
| `--columns` | `-c` | Display scripts in column format |
| `--update` | `-u` | Check for and install updates from repository |
| `--force` | `-f` | Force update even if version is the same |
| `--help` | `-h` | Show help message with usage information |
| `--version` | `-v` | Display script version |

### Option Details

#### Default (No Options)

```bash
scripts
```

**Behavior:**
- Lists all executable scripts in `~/.scripts`
- Displays full metadata for each script:
  - Script Name (in green)
  - Description
  - Usage instructions
  - Author
  - Date
  - Version
- Output is paginated using `less` with color support
- Use arrow keys or Page Up/Down to navigate
- Press `q` to quit

**Example Output:**
```
List of available scripts
awslogin
--------------------------------------
Script Name:    awslogin
Description:    Dynamically sets AWS default profile after SSO login
Usage:          awslogin [profile_name]
Author:         Julio Cesar Garcia
Date:           2025-03-15
Version:        4.5

edit
--------------------------------------
Script Name:    edit
Description:    Edits an existing script or creates a new one
Usage:          edit [script_name]
Author:         Julio Cesar Garcia
Date:           2025-03-05
Version:        2.5
```

#### Show Mode (`-s`, `--show`)

```bash
scripts -s
scripts --show
```

**Behavior:**
- Displays only script names
- Output in green color for easy visibility
- Formatted in columns to fit terminal width
- No pagination (entire list shown at once)

**Example Output:**
```
List of available scripts
awslogin          awsaccess         awsaddprofile     awsinstall
awsmoveaccount    awsnewaccount     awsorg            awsres
createawsaccount  CreateOrganization createOrgAdm     connecttoaws
device            edit              getamiinfo        gitproject
installextras     installscripts    listownamis       ocires
scripts           setupX11Forwarding wslops          azlogin
```

**Use Case:** Quick overview to find a specific script name.

#### Update Mode (`-u`, `--update`)

```bash
scripts -u
scripts --update
```

**Behavior:**
1. Downloads latest `installscripts` from GitHub repository
2. Compares local version with remote version
3. Displays version information
4. If update available:
   - Prompts for confirmation
   - Runs `installscripts` to update all scripts
   - Shows update progress
5. If already up-to-date:
   - Displays confirmation message
   - Provides tip about force update

**Example Session:**
```
==================================
  Checking for Updates
==================================

Checking for updates from repository...

Local version:  3.5
Remote version: 3.6

→ Updates available!

Do you want to update your scripts? (y/n): y

Running installation/update process...

[installscripts runs...]

==================================
  Update Complete!
==================================
```

**Use Case:** Regular maintenance to keep scripts current.

#### Force Update Mode (`-f`, `--force`)

```bash
scripts -f
scripts --force
```

**Behavior:**
- Bypasses version check
- Forces reinstallation even if versions match
- Useful for:
  - Recovering from corrupted installations
  - Reinstalling after manual modifications
  - Getting latest changes between version bumps

**Example Session:**
```
==================================
  Checking for Updates
==================================

Checking for updates from repository...

Local version:  3.5
Remote version: 3.5

→ Force update requested - reinstalling scripts...

Running installation/update process...

[installscripts runs...]

==================================
  Update Complete!
==================================
```

**Use Case:** Troubleshooting or ensuring clean installation.

---

## Viewing Modes

### Detailed View (Default)

**When to use:** 
- Exploring available scripts
- Learning what each script does
- Finding usage instructions

**Features:**
- Complete metadata display
- Color-coded output (green names, cyan details)
- Paginated for easy navigation
- Preserves colors in `less` viewer

**Navigation:**
- `↓` / `↑` - Line by line
- `Space` - Next page
- `b` - Previous page
- `/pattern` - Search
- `n` - Next search match
- `q` - Quit

### Compact View (`-s`)

**When to use:**
- Quick reference
- Finding script by name
- Terminal with limited space

**Features:**
- Names only, no descriptions
- Column layout optimized for terminal width
- All visible without scrolling (usually)
- Green highlighting

### Column View (`-c`)

**When to use:**
- Maximum density
- Alphabetical scanning

**Features:**
- Multi-column layout
- Minimal spacing
- Alphabetically sorted

---

## Update Management

### Version Checking

The update system compares version numbers from script headers:

```bash
# Version: 3.5
```

**Process:**
1. Download remote `installscripts` to temporary directory
2. Extract version from local file: `grep -i '^# Version:'`
3. Extract version from remote file
4. Compare versions
5. Decide action

### Update Workflow

**Automatic Update (`-u`):**
```
Check Connection → Download → Compare Versions → Prompt → Update → Cleanup
```

**Force Update (`-f`):**
```
Check Connection → Download → Skip Comparison → Update → Cleanup
```

### Update Sources

**Primary Repository:**
```
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ingasti/jcscripts/main/
```

**Files Downloaded:**
- `installscripts` (version check and execution)
- Through `installscripts`: All scripts in collection

### Update Safety

**Safeguards:**
- ✅ Temporary directory for downloads
- ✅ Version comparison before update
- ✅ User confirmation (unless forced)
- ✅ Automatic cleanup on success or failure
- ✅ Error messages for network issues

**What Gets Updated:**
- All scripts in the collection
- Configuration templates (if missing)
- Library files (`colorfunctions`, `wslfunctions`, etc.)
- Documentation files

**What's Preserved:**
- User configuration (`~/.jcscripts`)
- Custom scripts (not in repository)
- Log files
- Backup files

---

## Examples

### Example 1: Daily Script Discovery

```bash
# Quick list to find a script name
scripts -s
```

**Output:**
```
List of available scripts
awslogin    awsaccess    device    edit    gitproject    wslops
```

### Example 2: Learning About a Specific Script

```bash
# View all details
scripts
```

**Then:**
1. Use `/` to search: `/awslogin`
2. Press `n` to find next match
3. Read the description and usage
4. Press `q` to exit

### Example 3: Weekly Maintenance

```bash
# Check for updates every week
scripts --update
```

**Typical session:**
```
Local version:  3.5
Remote version: 3.5

✓ Your scripts are up to date!
```

### Example 4: Troubleshooting Corrupted Installation

```bash
# Force clean reinstall
scripts --force
```

### Example 5: Discovering New Scripts After Update

```bash
# Update first
scripts -u

# Then view what's available
scripts -s
```

### Example 6: Finding Script Version Information

```bash
# See all versions at once
scripts | grep "Version:"
```

---

## Configuration

### Configuration File Location

The `scripts` command reads configuration from:

1. `~/.jcscripts` (primary location)
2. `~/.scripts/.jcscripts` (fallback)

### Configuration Variables

```bash
# Example ~/.jcscripts
SCRIPTS_DIR="~/.scripts"      # Where scripts are stored
EDITOR="vi"                   # Editor for edit command
```

### Default Values

If no configuration file is found:

```bash
SCRIPTS_DIR="$HOME/.scripts"
EDITOR="vi"
```

### Configuration Notes

- `SCRIPTS_DIR` can use `~` which will be expanded to `$HOME`
- Changes to `SCRIPTS_DIR` affect where scripts are discovered
- Created automatically by `installscripts`

---

## Troubleshooting

### Problem: "No scripts found"

**Symptoms:**
```
No valid scripts found in ~/.scripts.
```

**Causes:**
- Directory doesn't exist
- No executable scripts
- Permission issues

**Solutions:**

```bash
# Check if directory exists
ls -la ~/.scripts

# If missing, run installation
cd ~/.scripts && ./installscripts

# Check permissions
chmod +x ~/.scripts/*

# Verify PATH includes scripts directory
echo $PATH | grep ".scripts"
```

### Problem: Update fails with network error

**Symptoms:**
```
ERROR: Unable to download updates from repository.
Please check your internet connection and try again.
```

**Solutions:**

```bash
# Test connectivity
ping -c 3 github.com

# Try manual download
curl -I https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ingasti/jcscripts/main/installscripts

# Check proxy settings
echo $HTTP_PROXY
echo $HTTPS_PROXY

# If behind proxy, set:
export HTTPS_PROXY="http://proxy.example.com:8080"
```

### Problem: Colors not showing

**Symptoms:**
- Script names not green
- Details not cyan
- No colors in output

**Solutions:**

```bash
# Check if colorfunctions exists
ls -l ~/.scripts/colorfunctions

# If missing, reinstall
cd ~/.scripts && ./installscripts

# Test terminal color support
tput colors
# Should return 8, 16, 256, or higher

# Check TERM variable
echo $TERM
# Should be xterm-256color or similar
```

### Problem: Pagination not working

**Symptoms:**
- All output scrolls past
- Can't navigate with arrow keys

**Solutions:**

```bash
# Check if 'less' is installed
which less

# Install less if missing
sudo apt install less          # Ubuntu/Debian
sudo dnf install less          # Fedora
sudo pacman -S less            # Arch
sudo apk add less              # Alpine

# Alternative: use -s for non-paginated output
scripts -s
```

### Problem: Wrong scripts directory

**Symptoms:**
- Scripts shows empty or unexpected results
- Recently installed scripts don't appear

**Solutions:**

```bash
# Check configuration
cat ~/.jcscripts

# Verify SCRIPTS_DIR value
grep SCRIPTS_DIR ~/.jcscripts

# If wrong, edit configuration
nano ~/.jcscripts

# Or recreate configuration
cd ~/.scripts && ./installscripts -c
```

### Problem: Update shows old version after updating

**Symptoms:**
```
Local version:  3.5
Remote version: 3.6
# But after update still shows 3.5
```

**Solutions:**

```bash
# Force update
scripts -f

# If still wrong, check for multiple installations
which scripts

# Should show only ~/.scripts/scripts
# If multiple, remove duplicates

# Verify version manually
grep "Version:" ~/.scripts/scripts
```

---

## Technical Details

### Script Detection Logic

**Finding Scripts:**
```bash
find "$SCRIPTS_DIR" -maxdepth 1 \( -type f -o -type l \) -executable ! -name ".*" ! -name "*.*"
```

**Filters:**
- `maxdepth 1` - Top level only (no subdirectories)
- `type f -o -type l` - Regular files or symbolic links
- `executable` - Must have execute permission
- `! -name ".*"` - Exclude hidden files
- `! -name "*.*"` - Exclude files with extensions

**Validation:**
```bash
file {} + | grep "ASCII text executable"
```

Ensures files are actual shell scripts.

### Metadata Extraction

**Header Pattern:**
```bash
grep -E "^(# *(Script Name|Description|Usage|Author|Date|Version):)" "$script"
```

**Process:**
1. Match lines starting with `#` and field name
2. Remove `# ` prefix
3. Filter out template variables
4. Display in color

**Filtering:**
```bash
sed -e 's/^# *//' \
    -e '/\$script_name/d' \
    -e '/\$LOGNAME/d' \
    -e '/\$(date/d'
```

Removes template placeholders from newly created scripts.

### Update Mechanism

**Download:**
```bash
curl -sSL "$repo_url/installscripts" -o "$temp_dir/installscripts"
```

**Flags:**
- `-s` - Silent (no progress bar)
- `-S` - Show errors
- `-L` - Follow redirects

**Version Extraction:**
```bash
grep -i '^# Version:' "$file" | awk -F': ' '{print $2}'
```

**Execution:**
```bash
chmod +x "$temp_dir/installscripts"
"$temp_dir/installscripts"
```

### Color Display

**Dependencies:**
- `colorfunctions` library
- `tput` command for terminal control
- `less -R` for color preservation in pager

**Functions Used:**
- `printgreen()` - Script names
- `printcyan()` - Metadata fields
- `printred()` - Error messages

### Performance Considerations

**Optimization:**
- Single `find` command for discovery
- Minimal external command calls
- Efficient pipe processing
- Cached `tput cols` for column width

**Scalability:**
- Handles 100+ scripts efficiently
- Pagination prevents memory issues
- Column calculation adapts to terminal size

---

## Quick Reference

### Common Commands

```bash
# List all scripts with details
scripts

# Quick name lookup
scripts -s

# Check for updates
